    "summary": "The Fall of Babylon to Persia (539 BC) was the swift and largely bloodless conquest of the greatest city in the ancient world by Cyrus the Great's armies — ending the Neo-Babylonian Empire and marking the beginning of Persian dominance over the Near East. Babylonian sources including the Nabonidus Chronicle describe Cyrus's general Ugbaru crossing the Tigris, and the city falling without a significant battle — possibly because its gates were opened by a pro-Persian faction or because the population, alienated by Nabonidus's religious policies, offered little resistance.\n\nCyrus entered Babylon in triumph, greeted (according to his own account) by the welcoming populace. He prayed to Marduk, respected the city's religious institutions, and declared himself the protector of Babylon rather than its destroyer — a brilliant contrast to Sennacherib's earlier destruction of the city. The fall of Babylon was a watershed event: it transferred control of the entire Fertile Crescent — Mesopotamia, Syria, and the Levant — to Persia in a single campaign, and allowed the Jewish exiles (see [[event:1908|Babylonian Captivity Judah]]) to begin their return to Judea. The Book of Daniel 5 depicts the fall dramatically with the 'writing on the wall' during Belshazzar's feast — a vivid legendary account of the night the empire ended.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fall_of_Babylon",
